@node MAINWINDOW "Main window"
@{b}Main window@{ub}


Doubleclick on a listview entry launches preferred web browser and loads the
page into it. Pressing RMB popups context menu for an entry.


Lamp images show status of checking operation:


@{b}*@{ub}  blue - disabled,

@{b}*@{ub}  dark green - idle,

@{b}*@{ub}  light green - tested succesfully, if a site was updated since the last
check, its address is printed in bold.

@{b}*@{ub}  yellow - loading data, "Length" field is periodically updated during loading,

@{b}*@{ub}  orange - connecting,

@{b}*@{ub}  red - error.

@endnode

@node DTFMTED "Date format editor"
@{b}Date settings@{ub}


Date settings window consists of @{u}date format editor@{uu} and miscellaneous
@{u}date settings@{uu}. You can set how dates taken from the website will be
handled. Generally SeventhSense has two sources of modification date of a
website. The first one is "Last-Modified" field in a HTTP header of server
response. This date is always given in Greenwich Mean Time. It is reliable date
fot static webpages (sent from static disk files). For dynamically generated
content (for example PHP scripts) web server doesn't pass "Last-Modified"
usually, or in some cases, the date is useless containing just the time of the
request. If HTTP header date is wrong, you can make SeventhSense to ignore it
unchecking "Use date from HTTP response header if present" checkmark.


What to do, when there is no date in the HTTP response, or this date is useless?
SeventhSense can search for dates in the webpage body. Fortunately most of
dynamically generated webpages have dates, for example news portals usually have
date with every news item, some sites have also "last updated" date. You can
define a date pattern using date format editor, which is explained later. Dates
on websites need not to be given in GMT time, they usually are of time zone
local to website creator. For example European websites can use CET time.
SeventhSense allow you to specify time zone for dates on every monitored
website, then all the dates can be uniformly presented to user in her local time
(according to the system locale settings). If the website shifts dates with one
hour in the summer (Daylight Save Time) you should check appropriate checkmark
in the "Date settings" (note this has nothing to do with usage of DST on your
computer).


The date format editor is used for creating date pattern for a website. The
program will use this pattern to search for the date through website contents (HTML code).
Use drag&drop to edit the date format. Available @{"date elements" LINK DATEELEMS} can
be dropped to date format list. To delete item from date format, drag it back to available
elements. Items in the format list can be also sorted with drag&drop. An example of
date in defined format is constantly displayed in a textfield below. Read also
about @{"date hunting" LINK DATEHUNT}.

@endnode

@node DATEHUNT "Date hunting"
@{b}Date hunting@{ub}


Searching for dates is a very good mean of checking dynamically generated
webpages for updates. It is usually more efficient and precise than plain
comparing the old and new contents. As dates may be written in many formats,
SeventhSense allows the user to specify date format for every monitored website
with @{"date format editor" LINK DTFMTED}. Date pattern consists of verbatim
strings (these parts are always the same and independent of current date) and
@{"date elements" LINK DATEELEMS} like year, month, hour, etc. Let's look at example below to learn
how to compose date pattern for a website.


Amiga Network News (http://www.ann.lu) is a well known Amiga news portal. Let's
try to monitor it with SeventhSense. It is rather easy, as we can see the date
of the last update under the ANN logo in the upper left corner. After adding the
site to the list, we open "Date settings" window. Before we start to compose the
pattern, we should look at the page source, as there can be some @{i}&nbsp;@{ui} or other
invisible HTML entities in the date. We can also use HTML tags surrounding the
date as verbatim strings to make searching more precise. Looking at the source
we can find the date, and it looks (the date is an example of course) as follows:


<BR>17-Dec-2004 12:36 GMT</TD>


Then we can define the date format dragging following items on "Date format"
listview in the "Date settings" window:


@{b}*@{ub}  verbatim string, enter "<BR>" in the popup,

@{b}*@{ub}  day, two digits with leading zero,

@{b}*@{ub}  verbatim string, enter "-" in the popup,

@{b}*@{ub}  month, three letters of English name,

@{b}*@{ub}  verbatim string, enter "-" in the popup,

@{b}*@{ub}  year, 4 digits,

@{b}*@{ub}  verbatim string, enter " " (space) in the popup,

@{b}*@{ub}  hour (24 hours, leading zero),

@{b}*@{ub}  verbatim string, enter ":" in the popup,

@{b}*@{ub}  minute,

@{b}*@{ub}  verbatim string, enter " GMT</TD>".


As it is explicitly said the time is GMT, you can leave default GMT time
zone and uncheck DST checkmark. Then click "OK", you've done.


@endnode

@node DATEELEMS "Date elements"
@{b}Date elements@{ub}


@{u}verbatim string@{uu} - is just a constant string, independent of current
date.


@{u}year (4 digits)@{uu} - full year number like "1997" or "2004".


@{u}year (2 digits)@{uu} - short year number, if greater than 77, 20-th century is
assumed ("82" means 1982). If lower or equal 77, 21-st century is assumed ("04"
means 2004).


@{u}month (2 digits, leading zero@{uu} - two-digit month number with leading zero.
Range is from "01" for January to "12" for December.


@{u}month (English, 3 letters)@{uu} - English 3-letter abbreviation of the month
name, for example "Jan", "May", "Oct".


@{u}day (2 digits, leading zero)@{uu} - two-digit day of the month number with
leading zero. Range from "01" to "28"/"29"/"30"/"31" depending on the month.


@{u}hours (24 hours, leading zero)@{uu} - two-digit number of hour in 24-hour
system, with leading zero. Range from "00" to "23".


@{u}minutes@{uu} - number of minutes in a hour, always with leading zero, range
from "00" to "59".


@{u}seconds@{uu} - number of seconds in a minute, always with leading zero,
range from "00" to "59".


@{u}month (English, full name)@{uu} - the full English name of a month.
Examples: "January", "May", "October".


@{u}weekday (English, 3 letters)@{uu} - three-letter abbreviation of English
weekday name. Examples: "Mon", "Thu", "Sat".


@{u}weekdany (English, full name)@{uu} - the full English name of a weekday.
Examples: "Monday", "Thursday", "Saturday".


@{u}day (1 or 2 digits)@{uu} - day number of the month, without any leading
character, so it can be 1 or 2 digits long. Range from "1" to "31". Note: the next character in the
pattern must not be a decimal digit.


@{u}hour (24 hours, 1 or 2 digits)@{uu} - hour in 24-hour system without any
leading character, so it can be 1 or 2 digits long. Range from "0" to "23". Note: the next character
in the pattern must not be a decimal digit.


@{u}month (1 or 2 digits)@{uu} - month number without any leading character, so
it can be 1 or 2 digits long. Range from "1" to "12". Note: The next character in the pattern must not
be a decimal digit.


@{u}ordinal number (up to 6 digits)@{uu} - a number somehow counting up with a site update. Typically
it will be an ordinal number of news item, placed for example in a link to comments. Useful for sites
with no dates attached to news items. Up to 6 decimal digits, with or without leading zeros.


@{u}any single character@{uu} - matches any single character the same as '?' in DOS filename. Shown on
the example field as highlighted question mark (then you know it is wildchar, not part of verbatim string). Useful
for skipping not meaning but changing parts of date pattern. Typical example is skipping an English
ordinal numeral suffix (-st, -nd, -rd, -th), it can be replaced by two wildchars.

@endnode

